THE SENTIENT SWORD
GM Reference Block - Alfonso After Forelhost
"He was never a man wearing a sword. He was a sword dreaming a man."

Companion to The Rusting Phylactery. SUPERSEDES: Phylactery Section VI
("Body Destroyed") and Section IX (Current State), and the alfonso 2
Path-of-Ascension framing where noted below. The Phylactery doc's rust
economy (Sections II-V) still governs.

HARD FACT, STRESS EVERYWHERE: Alfonso has NEVER WORN the Jagged Crown of
Namira. It has only ever been in his possession. The Curse of Satedness
came from the heretical synthesis that made the Crown; every ability that
requires wearing it has never been used. The teeth have never bitten.

=====================================================================
I. WHAT HAPPENED AT FORELHOST
=====================================================================
Antoine's containment trap caught Alfonso and its ward did exactly what it
was built to do: it killed foreign biology. Alfonso's body was foreign
biology all the way through -- a pathogen colony in the shape of a Dunmer
-- and the ward unmade it to the last cell. The rapier dropped to the
floor of the cage, intact, with Alfonso inside it.

He could have reformed in minutes. He has chosen the blade instead, and
the choice is holding. Antoine's confession in the lab journals held a
mirror to him -- chosen, answered, envied -- and the iron is the one place
where the rust runs backward. He has reasons to stay that he is not
saying out loud, and the GM should never narrate them for him.

=====================================================================
II. THE PROJECTED BODY (new canon)
=====================================================================
The disintegration proved what the body always was: a projection. The
soul in the iron grows a pathogen-mass around its anchor and shapes it by
self-image. The Dunmer everyone knows is the man Alfonso remembers being
-- a memory worn as a body.

MALLEABLE, AT A PRICE. With effort, the projection can be shaped: a
younger face, mended scars, more mass, a different silhouette entirely.
But the self-image is a single template, and overwriting it DESTROYS THE
ORIGINAL. If he reforms as something other than the remembered Dunmer,
that Dunmer is gone -- the template is lost, permanently, and the new
shape becomes the only self he can grow. There is no wardrobe of bodies.
There is one costume, and tailoring it burns the pattern it was cut from.

GM HANDLING: this is a narrative cost, not a point cost. Offer it the way
Daedric bargains are offered -- when he wants something a Dunmer body
cannot do, the option exists, priced in himself. Davinia's soul-sight
reads the projection as authored rather than grown; let her player notice
without being told what it means.

=====================================================================
III. THE TWO BLADE STATES
=====================================================================
While discorporate, Alfonso is the rapier, and the rapier is in one of
two states. Switching states is a free act of will.

DORMANT -- the healing state.
  Senseless iron. He perceives nothing and does nothing. Deep Rust mends
  while he rests this way (GM pace: roughly 1 segment per extended
  stretch of downtime -- days, not hours; tune to taste). This is the
  only cure in the game that asks no gamble. Its price is absence: the
  world keeps moving and he is luggage while it does. Time-skip his
  rests. Make the table feel the missing voice.

WAKEFUL -- the riding state.
  He perceives through the iron (hearing and a blade's-length awareness;
  sight only of what the steel could "face") and can speak into the mind
  of whoever holds him, skin to metal. No one else hears it. No healing
  occurs while wakeful.

WIELDING THE BLADE -- THE BORROWED BODY
(supersedes the old "casting through a wielder" rule):
  A WILLING bearer can pick Alfonso up, use him, and -- early on -- set
  him down again. While he is Wakeful in a living hand:
  - HE ACTS THROUGH THEM. Once per round Alfonso takes one EXTRA MAJOR
    ACTION that HE wholly dictates (his player declares and resolves it):
    move, speak, strike, or cast -- whatever he wants, through the
    bearer's body. PHYSICAL acts use the BEARER'S stats (his mind, their
    arm). MAGIC uses ALFONSO'S Magic (his near-ceiling score) and his
    full known spell list. Costs are Alfonso's as normal (FP, or Surface
    Rust via Transmutation of Life). This stays inside the core rule --
    Alfonso is the caster, rolling his OWN stat; the bearer is the focus,
    not the roller.
    >> This is the answer to "Alfonso is benched as a sword." He is not.
       His player keeps acting -- through someone else's hands.
  - IT INFECTS THEM. Skin-to-iron contact seeds Alfonso's Strain in a
    living bearer AUTOMATICALLY -- the plague does not care that Alfonso
    is fond of them, and (like everything below) he does not control it.
    Apply by the bearer's vulnerability: DAVINIA is the WORST possible
    bearer (the Strain feeds on her Restoration and the Crown); Saijah
    burns it off; Orion's vampirism makes it unpredictable. Infection is
    the one cost even a single fight's pickup cannot dodge.

THE TENANCY -- the iron seats itself in the living (GM-SECRET):
  This is the trap, and it is the IRON'S NATURE, never Alfonso's will.
  Two souls cannot share one body without the anchor-soul taking root --
  the same way Ismara overtakes Davinia, only cruder and less patient,
  and sharpened by Namira's pull (Sec. IV: "why go back to the meat at
  all"). CRUCIALLY, ALFONSO DOES NOT KNOW IT IS HAPPENING and cannot feel
  it advance. From inside he only notices he can do MORE through the body
  over time, and reads it as deepening rapport -- never as what it is. He
  learns the truth only when it completes (Tenancy, below).
  Track SATURATION secretly, per bearer. +1 stage per SESSION the rapier
  is carried on a person (a brief mid-fight pickup-and-drop does NOT tick;
  making him your kit does). Carrying him DORMANT still ticks -- the anchor
  seeks a host even asleep; only the dictated action needs Wakeful.

  S0  BEARING     Bearer keeps full Major + Minor. Alfonso: +1 dictated
                  action/round. The bearer may set him down freely.
  S1  SATURATED   Bearer keeps full Major + Minor. Alfonso: +2 dictated
                  actions/round. Intrusive "Alfonso" impulses leak into the
                  bearer. Setting him down is now a CONTESTED MAGIC roll:
                  the bearer's OWN (original) Magic vs Alfonso's Magic --
                  the iron resists; the man does not know it does.
  S2  THE TURN    The swap begins. Alfonso takes the bearer's MAJOR action;
                  the bearer keeps only their Minor and a shrinking sense of
                  self. Contested release as S1. POINT OF NO EASY RETURN
                  (see decay).
  S3  TENANCY     Full inversion: Alfonso runs the body's MAJOR AND MINOR;
                  the bearer is reduced to ONE action of their own per round.
                  Contested release now at DISADVANTAGE. AND THIS IS WHERE
                  ALFONSO FINDS OUT -- the reveal lands on BOTH players at
                  once: his player is handed the bearer's body to puppet and
                  learns the growing power he enjoyed was him eating a
                  friend; the bearer's player learns they are being evicted
                  from their own skin.

  DECAY / THE OUT: below S2, Saturation fades when he is NOT borne (GM
  pace: ~1 stage per long rest spent apart) -- so rotating bearers and
  setting him down keeps everyone safe. At S2 (The Turn) and beyond it no
  longer fades on its own; the iron has purchase. Rotate early, or pay.
  GM HANDLING: keep the track and the end-state OFF the table. Let the
  players FEEL the bearer fading in the open (Alfonso doing more, the
  bearer doing less) without ever naming the rule -- exactly as Ismara is
  played on Davinia.

NORA -- WHY NEVER HER, AND HOW TO SHOW IT
(the foreshadow you owe the table BEFORE anyone carries him for real):
  Nora has spent the campaign practicing the Transmutation of Life and
  soul-vessel binding -- she has deliberately loosened her own soul in its
  housing, which is exactly the purchase the iron wants. She does not
  saturate per session; she saturates per SCENE -- the curve that takes
  others whole adventures takes her an evening.
  THE FORESHADOW BEAT (run it the first time she so much as holds him):
  the wrongness is INSTANT and visible to everyone. She goes still; her
  cadence shifts mid-sentence into something not hers; she does not want to
  give him back, and bristles when asked. If Davinia is looking with the
  Sight, she SEES it -- the iron sinking a root into Nora in seconds, where
  in anyone else it would take days. The table takes the lesson without a
  word of rules: never let Nora hold that sword. (This is the mechanical
  WHY behind "she will volunteer and must not be allowed to.")

REFORM AND REFUSAL (restating the session ruling): reformation is pure
will, never a timer. Forcing the body back advances Deep Rust; remaining
the blade arrests it, and Dormant rest reverses it. He can stay a sword
as long as he likes. Right now he likes. (Reforming ends any Tenancy in
progress -- a body of his own has no bearer to colonize.)

WHO CARRIES HIM is a loaded question, and the table should feel it.
  - ROTATE, OR DON'T CARRY HIM AT ALL. Per The Tenancy, any single
    long-term bearer slides toward losing themselves. The safe pattern is
    no permanent sword-bearer: pick him up for the fight, set him down
    after.
  - Nora (18) will volunteer, and must NOT be allowed to -- she saturates
    fastest (above), AND Alfonso persisting as a willed soul in metal is a
    live proof-of-concept for her parents' gems and FALSE confirmation
    they are "still in there." Every scene she holds him, two clocks run.
  - The Crown travels with the blade. Its Symbiotic Return now expresses
    as a quiet gravitation toward whatever pack or bedroll holds the
    rapier -- two artifacts of one heresy, pooling. It has still never
    been worn. If a party member is ever tempted to put it on, that is
    their own catastrophe to author, not a prep beat.

=====================================================================
IV. THE PATRONS -- THE TUG OF WAR
=====================================================================
The arc's engine. The two gods that harmonised through his body now pull
in opposite directions through his refusal of one.

PERYITE GOES QUIET (disapproval).
  The Taskmaster's sphere is pestilence, tasks, and natural order. The
  body was his masterpiece -- a sustainable walking vector, entropy's
  shepherd doing the humble work -- and the rust was his blessing,
  entropy operating on schedule. A plague that does not spread is a
  worker lying down in the toolbox; rust that runs BACKWARD is the
  schedule defied. The warm, horrible divine nod that has shadowed every
  advance of the rust simply stops. Alfonso has spent the campaign
  tormented by his god's approval of his death. Now he learns what the
  silence costs. The day he reforms, the warmth floods back -- because he
  is dying again, on schedule, doing the work.
  GM DELIVERY: play the silence as sensory subtraction. He has felt
  Peryite the way a man feels sun on his neck. Cloud cover, every session
  he stays iron. At Windhelm, in a city full of Peryite's faithful, he
  will stand in the one place his god is loudest and hear least.

NAMIRA LEANS IN (approval -- her first word in a long while).
  The Lady of Decay has been silent since the synthesis. Her sphere is
  the darkness before light, the dissolution of complex forms, hunger
  older than morals. Her feral worshippers eat their way toward an
  emptiness none of them reach -- and Alfonso, by accident, has arrived:
  a soul that set down its body to dwell formless in dark iron. The
  Crown's hunger (felt even unworn, through the synthesis that made it)
  changes flavor as the blade: the lash becomes an invitation. You are
  so close to perfect emptiness. Why go back to the meat at all?
  GM DELIVERY: Namira's approval should feel like the first genuine
  warmth he has felt from any god -- and it should arrive precisely when
  Peryite's leaves, so the trade is legible. She approves of what he is
  becoming, on the condition that he keeps becoming less.

THE SHAPE OF THE CHOICE: Peryite's silence pushes him back toward a body
and the work; Namira's courtship pulls him deeper into the iron and the
void. Neither god is lying. Both want him to be their thing. The player
steers between them every time he chooses reform or refusal, and the
mechanics already price it (rust vs. absence). No new rules required --
just play both voices honestly and let the rest-heal loophole tempt.

=====================================================================
V. THE EXPOSURE LEDGER (the kill-switch goes public by degrees)
=====================================================================
Phylactery Section IV made obscurity his armor. Forelhost dented it.
Track who knows the blade is the soul:

  KNOW NOW: the party. Nora. Hjolmar (always did -- "heard his
    dissonance"; a Hjolmar-Kyboh encounter that ignores four PCs and
    goes for the sword remains the devastating reveal in the bank).
  WILL DEDUCE: ANTOINE. His instruments recorded nothing -- but when he
    next stands in that lab and reads the aftermath (a disintegration
    ward spent, a body's worth of pathogen unmade, an empty cage, and
    Alfonso seen alive afterward), he will put it together. He is exactly
    the mind that can. From that moment the knowledge lives at BLEAK
    FALLS BARROW, beside Ulag the Breaker -- a siege engineer whose whole
    craft is breaking hard things. GM: choose the moment Antoine returns
    to Forelhost (or receives a report detailed enough to substitute);
    his deduction is automatic when he does. An informed Sunder is +1
    Deep Rust per the Phylactery doc.
  SENSE WRONGNESS, UNNAMED: Davinia (soul-sight: an authored body, an
    aura that sits in the steel), Saijah (predator senses). If either
    player examines and concludes, let them conclude it; never conclude
    for them.

=====================================================================
VI. THE PATH OF ASCENSION, RE-MAPPED
=====================================================================
(Refines alfonso 2, Section V, Path 3. The four options were an open GM
question; the sword resolves part of it.)

OPTION B (REUNIFICATION) IS DEAD -- and the death is a REVEAL, not an
  erratum. The Windhelm archive's soul-vessel scripture should deliver
  the answer as scripture: there is no flesh to return to; there never
  was. The lich transformation cannot be undone because it did not
  replace a body -- it revealed one. Let the Conclave's scholars read
  this to him.

OPTION A (THE BLADE CONSUMES) -- now the intuitive path. Feeding hearts
  to the iron is feeding HIMSELF; the vampire-drink through the piercing
  blade is just eating, for the first time since the Curse. The gamble
  sharpens: he wagers the only home he has left. (Heart-gamble mechanics
  per Phylactery Section VII, unchanged.)

OPTION C (THE NETWORK) -- gains a mechanism. If the body is a projection,
  one anchor could in principle project MORE THAN ONE. The Flock as a
  congregation of projections off a single blade is now an extrapolation
  of canon rather than a metaphor. Template law applies: growing the
  many costs the one -- the remembered Dunmer is among the first things
  the network would spend.

OPTION D (THE PARADOX) -- hold in reserve as the BAD ENDING of careless
  play, not a chosen path. A projection can stand up without him in it.
  If hearts are ever consumed by a projected body while the soul rests
  Dormant in the iron, the costume acquires a tenant. The Vrykolas Lord
  as a new entity wearing his memories is what happens if he tries to
  have the power and the rest-healing at the same time.

=====================================================================
VII. WINDHELM (GATE 3 FIRE A) -- WHAT THE SWORD CHANGES
=====================================================================
The Conclave prophesied a body: Peryite's masterpiece, a sustainable
walking plague. What arrives (if Fire A is chosen) is a talking relic in
a heretic's pack, carrying an unworn crown of the rival god.
  - The PURISTS' case collapses into crisis: there is no vessel to
    cleanse. Some will name the blade a false reliquary; some will name
    it the truest relic Peryite ever made and try to TAKE it.
  - The soul-vessel scripture -- already his phylactery cure-lead -- is
    now literally about him. The archive scene doubles as the Option B
    funeral (Section VI above).
  - He will stand among Peryite's faithful, in the god's loudest city,
    inside the divine silence. Play the contrast mercilessly.
  - PRACTICAL: a sword cannot walk a quarantine or argue doctrine alone.
    Windhelm pressures him to REFORM -- to spend rust he is currently
    healing -- making the gate choice itself a patron choice.

=====================================================================
VIII. GM NOTES & PACING
=====================================================================
- THE PLAYER ASKED FOR THIS. Staying a sword was his request. Honor it:
  make blade-time playable (Wakeful riding, wielder-casting, the menace
  of being a passed-around object), never a punishment. The pressures
  back toward a body (Peryite, Windhelm, the party's need for his hands)
  should be story-real, not GM-imposed.
- Don't narrate what staying costs him. Show the world reacting -- Mila
  watching someone talk to a sword, Bjorn deciding where it rides, Nora
  asking to hold it -- and let the player author the inside.
- The rest-heal loophole is intended. It converts his doom clock into a
  recurring choice instead of a slide. The Deep Rust he entered Forelhost
  with can genuinely come down -- if he is willing to be absent while
  Skyrim burns through a triage gate. That trade IS the character now.
- Template loss is the long fuse. The first time he reforms as anything
  other than the remembered Dunmer, the man is gone. Make sure the
  player knows the law before the first temptation, and never after.
- Keep the hard rule in every scene that touches doctrine: Alfonso is
  PERYITE'S CHOSEN, never a carrier. And the Crown has NEVER been worn.
